                content="The question of how human language originated remains one of the most debated topics in linguistics and anthropology. Unlike other human achievements such as tool-making, which leave physical traces in the archaeological record, language leaves no direct fossil evidence. Scholars must therefore rely on indirect evidence, including the anatomy of vocal tracts in early hominids, the development of brain regions associated with speech, and comparisons with communication systems in other species.\n\n"
                "Several competing theories attempt to explain the emergence of language. The gestural theory proposes that language began as a system of hand gestures and only later transitioned to vocal communication. Proponents point to the close neurological connection between hand movements and speech production in the modern human brain. The social grooming hypothesis, advanced by anthropologist Robin Dunbar, suggests that language evolved as a more efficient substitute for the physical grooming that primates use to maintain social bonds. As human groups grew larger, vocal communication allowed individuals to strengthen relationships with multiple group members simultaneously.\n\n"
